Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read the Prime Minister’s address for the latest information.

We are assessing British nationals’ interest in a charter flight from Trinidad and Tobago to the UK. If you are a British national visiting Trinidad and Tobago, normally resident in the UK, and need to return to the UK urgently, let us know by emailing your details to stayincontactTRINIDADANDTOBAGO@fco.gov.uk. If you have already been in contact with us about returning to the UK you do not need to email again.
There are currently no commercial options available to return to the UK from Trinidad and Tobago. The Trinidad and Tobago government closed its borders to all international flights from midnight 22 March. Sea borders are also closed to all vessels including yachts.
British Airways have announced that they will not be operating scheduled commercial flights between Trinidad and Tobago and the UK until 30 June. The planned resumption date of 1 July is subject to change. Other airlines have not announced any plans to restart their commercial service in the Caribbean region. Travel advice will be updated with information about any flight options to the UK, as airlines notify us that they are available. If you’re affected by this, you should contact your airline directly. You can email your enquiries to stayincontactTRINIDADANDTOBAGO@fco.gov.uk and continue to follow our social media pages for updates.
We know this is concerning for British people trying to leave Trinidad and Tobago. The UK government is working closely with airlines, the Trinidad and Tobago authorities and other governments to make sure options are available for you to return to the UK as soon as possible
Future travel options
We are assessing British nationals’ interest in a charter flight from Trinidad and Tobago to the UK. If you are a British national visiting Trinidad and Tobago and normally resident in the UK, and need to return to the UK urgently, let us know by emailing your details to stayincontactTRINIDADANDTOBAGO@fco.gov.uk. If you have already been in contact with us about returning to the UK you do not need to email again.
Where possible, British Nationals in Trinidad and Tobago should monitor the following social media platforms for the latest available information on departure options:
Facebook @UKinTT
Twitter: @UKinCaribbean and @HCTimStew
Instagram: @UKinCaribbean and @TimStewFCO.
You should also sign up for travel advice email alerts.
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If departure options are available but you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK.
For more information, you should contact Corporate Travel Management (CTM). CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
This travel advice will be updated when departure options become available.
Your journey home
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Help and support
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the British High Commission on +1 868 350 0444 choose option 2, then option 1. You can also email your enquiry to stayincontactTRINIDADANDTOBAGO@fco.gov.uk.
The High Commission cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available. To get the latest information, sign up for travel advice email alerts and please follow our social media.
If you cannot leave Trinidad and Tobago
If you cannot leave Trinidad and Tobago at this time, see advice on staying in Trinidad and Tobago during coronavirus.
